This paper proposes a method for compressing deep neural networks (DNNs) for resource-constrained devices, which is a common problem in computer vision and machine learning applications. The paper focuses on factorizing weight matrices via singular value decomposition (SVD), which is a common technique in linear algebra and optimization. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper discusses the complexity of models, which is related to algorithms and data structures, suggesting cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the proposed method on multiple image-classification tasks, which is a common application of DNNs, suggesting cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as a possible sub-category.
